{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493020"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:53:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:53:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1202"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1202"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.33,0.18,0.15,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42539"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1202"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27502"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"664"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8753"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5611"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42539"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of increasing upper abdominal pain. The pain is colicky with associated nausea but no vomiting. Ten days earlier she underwent a laparoscopic Roux-en-Y gastric bypass. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus and obesity. Her medications include metformin and empagliflozin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70mmHg and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. She is tender in the epigastrium, around the site of her recent abdominal wound. A venous blood gas reveals a blood glucose of 12.1 mmol/L (3.2-5.5) and ketones of 1.1 mmol/L (\u0026lt;1). A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic ketoacidosis","Small bowel obstruction","Paralytic ileus","Gastric perforation","Large bowel obstruction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E. There is a massively dilated loop of small bowel in the right upper quadrant (can see this is fluid filled rather than faecalised as compared to the colon below it) and the large bowel is collapsed. This obstruction was the result of an internal hernia that had developed after the bypass procedure (SBO is often from internal hernia, adhesions, or strictures).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct answer. Whilst this condition can be associated with abdominal pain, along with nausea, the ketones are only mildly elevated (most likely due to dehydration) and her background of non-insulin dependent diabetes mellitus makes DKA fairly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParalytic ileus\u003C/strong\u003E can occur transiently in the post-operative period, but is considered pathological when it persists for \u0026gt;72 hours. Considering it is now ten days following the procedure, one would have expected any post-operative ileus to have resolved by now. As such, this is not the best answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the case of \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric perforation\u003C/strong\u003E, the CT would display free gas rather than than an appearance of intestinal obstruction. Furthermore, the onset of pain in the setting of perforation is sudden and acute, rather than a gradual build (such as in this case).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is significantly less likely to develop than a small bowel obstruction in this setting of a recent Roux-en-Y gastric bypass. Further more the CT shows dilated small bowel but collapsed large bowel which therefore excludes a large bowel obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Small bowel obstructions are often from internal hernia, adhesions, or strictures."],"references":["Aoki M, Saka M, Morita S, Fukagawa T, Katai H. Afferent loop obstruction after distal gastrectomy with Roux-en-Y reconstruction. World J Surg. 2010;34(10):2389-92. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20458583/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27502"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1202"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14301"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14301"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8bccfac-06cd-42ad-9b16-55f1faa9428f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8bccfac-06cd-42ad-9b16-55f1faa9428f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":516,"height":637}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27502"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-12T09:50:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-12T09:50:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1202"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42539"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":